english:
  title: Memorial of Petition
  author: Choi Yu-cheong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the eighteenth day of the third month of this year, when the envoys bearing imperial instructions—Lu Ling-ju and Hong Ruo-yi—returned, I received the imperial edict and supplementary records commanding us to swiftly identify and report the exact number of people from the empire who have sought refuge in our small realm. Upon hearing this mandate, my spirit trembled, and though I am as insignificant as grass and chaff, I must lay bare my humble sentiments once more, beseeching your divine compassion to regard me with pity. Reflecting upon my presumption, my anxiety only deepens.

    I humbly consider that I, a man of meager talent in a small nation, have had the fortune to witness the True One receive the Mandate of Heaven and establish great enterprises to unify all beneath heaven. Thus did I admire righteousness and come to court, taking my place as a tributary state and fulfilling our tribute obligations. Your Majesty practices profound benevolence, casting aside the net of punishment, and extends generous virtue to encompass the wild lands. You have recognized our nation's loyalty and bestowed upon us the kindness due to the small. In the fourth year of Tian Hui, in the fifth month, you sent Envoy Gao Bo-shu with imperial proclamations—both written and oral—declaring that Bazhou city would not be reclaimed, and that the people who had crossed over to us should become part of our realm at our convenience. I then descended the steps in reverence and received these luminous commands, and my people and I rejoiced and were grateful, our humble hearts already expressing thanks through written memorials.

    Again in the sixth year of Tian Hui, in the twelfth month, when Envoys Si Gu-de and Han Fang arrived bearing supplementary records, they declared: "Regarding Bazhou land, there was an initial imperial instruction that it would not be reclaimed. We understood that you would humbly preserve the ancient statutes and revere the imperial house, and thus the court, not sparing this territory, specially granted it to your nation. Yet after several years, you have still not submitted the oath-bearing memorial. How can this accord with propriety? Moreover, those who have fled or been forced away since then number considerably, yet all claim to have perished—a matter most unclear. Furthermore, the recent imperial edict permits Bazhou, yet contains no mention of 'one city and its borders,' and the boundaries have not been clearly delineated. Naturally, portions within your realm should be demarcated through proper agreement. In these several matters, if your nation demonstrates sincerity and promptly submits the oath-bearing memorial, the court shall likewise return an oath-bearing edict and further issue directives to establish your borders fairly and generously—this is a plan for lasting harmony."

    Moreover, Han Fang wrote to the officials of the embassy house: "The court now displays great faith to the realm—would it deceive your nation?" Hearing these clear proclamations and sensing this exceptional grace, I pointed to heaven and swore an oath, presenting this memorial in reverence. I expected that His Majesty's benevolence would graciously grant the oath-bearing edict. Yet now the imperial writ arrives repeatedly with ever-sterner instructions, leaving me bewildered and anxious, uncertain what course to take.

    Consider further: the matter of people who have come to our small state are trifles from before my late father, the Former King, could serve the great state—yet they are now pressed with such severity! This not only contradicts our nation's grateful reliance upon you, but I fear it may not accord with the court's intention to govern tributary states through supreme benevolence and great virtue. This is why I lay bare my heart and blood, daring to transgress against the celestial authority, unable to restrain myself.

    I humbly beseech you to turn your illuminating gaze upon us and grant us deep compassion. Following the precedent of the Former Kings in pacifying distant peoples, and employing the generous amnesty of the great Han toward the fugitive, I beg you specially to grant this sincere petition and extend the fullness of your mercy. Though our nation is small and without talent, we shall surely be moved to repay this grace. As the sunflower bends eternally toward the sun, and as the Yangtze and Han rivers flow ceaselessly toward the great ocean, so may Heaven and Earth witness the truth of these words.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'four directions' (四至) refers to the delineation of boundaries by establishing the limits to the east, west, south, and north.
  - key: ''
    value: The Former King referenced here is understood as a sage-king of antiquity, exemplifying virtuous rulership.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of the sunflower and rivers is a classical metaphor for the vassal's unwavering devotion to the sovereign.
